Forest recovery: Post-wildfire vegetation regrowth analysis after the Chimney Tops 2 Fire in Great Smoky Mountains National Park¶

Author: Stepan Bryleev (CU Boulder EarthLab student)
Industry supervisor: Bridget M. Hass (NEON Remote Sensing Data Scientist)
University supervisor: Dr. Elsa Culler (CU Boulder EarthLab Teacher)

2016 Chimney Tops 2 Fire¶

In late-November 2016, a forest fire started on Chimney Tops Mountain in Great Smoky Mountains National Park. Due to unseasonably dry and windy conditions, the fire grew several orders of magnitude in one day and spread uncontrollably throughout the national park towards the nearby town of Gatlinburg. The Chimney Top 2 fire caused major destruction that impacted homes, businesses and also resulted in fatalities and injuries. The Chimney Tops 2 wildfire was recorded as the largest fire in Great Smoky Mountains National Park history and is of great interest to a wide range of environmental scientists.

Remote sensing as the research method of growing threat¶

All around the world wildfires, such as the Chimney Tops 2 Fire, are becoming more frequent and more intense. So there is a greater need to study evolution of big wildfires and post fire ecological changes for maintaining resources, protecting ecosystems, people and properties. One such a way is to use remote sensing technologies to study fires from the air or from space. Remote sensing data can provide sufficient land area coverage and frequent measurements to study fires in detail and to better understand them.

During the Chimney Tops 2 Fire over 10,000 acres of Great Smoky Mountains National Park burned including the area in which two NEON field sites are located. Thus, detailed analysis of NEON remote sensing data can be used to identify vegetation regrowth dynamics inside the fire perimeter and evaluate post-fire ecological changes.

Data source selection¶

NEON began data collection activities at LeConte and Great Smoky Mountains in 2015, when the Airborne Observation Platform (AOP) flew over both sites collecting LiDAR, hyperspectral and high resolution RGB ortho-photos of the surrounding vegetation and landscape. The sites were flown again in the summer of 2016 at peak greenness, and the fall of 2017 past peak greenness. So, we are fortunate to have a little over one year's worth of pre-fire data and subsequent data on fire recovery. This allows to complete detailed analysis of the vegetation regrowth inside Chimney Top 2 fire perimeter.

Although the NEON spectrometer has high spatial resolution(1-meter) and is a great instrument, the reflectance data is typically collected by NEON only once a year. Moreover, in 2017 GRSM site was flown in fall of 2017 which is past peak greenness. So it is difficult to compose representative time series for estimating regrowth dynamics rates using only NIS data.

Since Landsat 8 orbits the Earth every 16 days, there is more reflectance data available. Thus, more frequent but lower spatial resolution (30-meter) Landsat 8 data was used to validate NEON data and provide a more comprehensive time series.

Study area and period¶

To estimate post-fire changes and recovery rates study reigion of 36.35 km2 was defined inside the CT2 fire perimeter. Unfortunately, due to weather and other operational reasons coverage area of NEON airborne observations in GRSM differs from year to year. To avoid "NO DATA" gaps, we selected the study polygon that excludes the presence of "NO DATA" pixels for both NEON reflectance and NEON Lidar data.

Initially, Canopy Height Models (CHMs) for 2016, 2017 and 2021 NEON AOP Lidar observations were calculated to estimate landscape changes.

Then we compared interannual AOP reflectance data measured by the NEON Imaging Spectrometer (NIS) in 2016, 2017 and 2021 with interannual data from the Operational Land Imager on the Landsat 8 satellite for a time period from 2015 to 2023.

All analysis was implemented in Google Earth Engine.

Results¶

Forest Canopy Height¶

First let's look at high resolution Canopy Height Models of difference (dCHMs) calculated using NEON Lidar data to estimate 2016/2017 and 2016/2021 canopy height difference.

Figure 1. dCHM between 2016 and 2017 for GRSM study area (height difference in meters).¶

It can be seen that the most part of the study area experienced significant loss of canopy height the year after the fire. Especially northern part of study polygon, around the town of Gatlinburg. In this regard, it is interesting to see how average tree height distribution has changed from 2016 to 2017.

Histogram 1. Histogram of 2016 canopy height distribution inside the GRSM study area (from NEON Lidar data).¶
Histogram 2. Histogram of 2017 canopy height distribution inside the GRSM study area (from NEON Lidar data).¶

Comparing two histograms above, we can conclude that the maximum tree height has shifted from 24-26 meters (in 2016) to ZERO (in 2017). Thus, it can be assumed that most of the burned forest was completely destroyed by fire. The second maximum of 2017 is near 20 meters and for canopy that presumably remained undamaged or partly survived.

What about regrowth?¶

Now let's look at the forest recovery for the period from 2017 to 2021.

Figure 2. dCHM between 2017 and 2021 for GRSM study area (height difference in meters).¶

It can be noted that an increase in canopy height is observed throughout all the northern part of the study area. However, in the southern part of the study region there are multiple areas of decrease in canopy height. On the 2021 histogram, there is a clearly seen new local maximum for newly appeared vegetation with a canopy height of 2-4 meters (Histogram 3.).

Histogram 3. Histogram of 2021 canopy height distribution inside the GRSM study area (from NEON Lidar data).¶

Mean Canopy Height by year¶

Generally, the following values of the mean canopy height were obtained from the NEON Lidar data for 2016, 2017 and 2021 (Figure 3).

Figure 3. Mean canopy height inside the GRSM study area by year.¶

It should be noted that the newly appeared vegetation can be tall grass and shrubs. Thus, determining the species composition of newly grown vegetation can be a great future work. Studying of post-fire canopy height patterns obtained from Lidar data really matters since it can help national park staff and professionals to better identify problem regions and put more effort into restoring these slow recovering areas.
